In `Services/FileService.cs`, the constructor calls `Directory.CreateDirectory(root)` during DI resolution. This couples service construction to disk I/O and can sink the entire application startup if the configured path is invalid or unwritable (the singleton is constructed during DI container build, so a thrown exception aborts startup with no useful diagnostic). Replace with thread-safe lazy initialization: change the `_root` field from `private readonly string _root;` to `private readonly Lazy<string> _rootLazy;`. In the constructor, only COMPUTE the path and store it in the Lazy — do not call `Directory.CreateDirectory` in the ctor. Configure the Lazy with `LazyThreadSafetyMode.ExecutionAndPublication` so the directory is created exactly once even under concurrent first-access. The Lazy's value factory should both create the directory and return the resolved root path. Expose the root via a `private string Root => _rootLazy.Value;` property and replace all internal reads of `_root` (in `SafeResolve`, `ToRelative`, and any other call sites) with `Root`. The public surface (constructor signature, all IFileService method signatures) is unchanged.

BEHAVIOR CHANGE — test impact: The existing tests `Constructor_CreatesRootDirectory_WhenItDoesNotExist` and `Constructor_SupportsNestedHomeDirectoryPath` (in FileServiceTests.cs) assert `Directory.Exists(root)` is true immediately AFTER constructing the service. With lazy init, the directory is not created until first method call. These tests must be updated (by the test-writing phase) to trigger lazy initialization FIRST — e.g., call `service.ResolveFullPath("")` or `service.Browse("")` — before asserting `Directory.Exists`. The test `Constructor_NullHomeDirectory_DefaultsToHome` similarly needs to trigger lazy init before asserting on `Directory.Exists`. The implementer should change the production code; the test-writing phase will update those three tests. Verify: `dotnet build TestProject.sln` succeeds; after the test updates, `dotnet test TestProject.Tests/TestProject.Tests.csproj` passes.

